            Greek migration crisis
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/greece-migration-pressure-thanos-plevris-response.jpg"
          alt="Thanos Plevris defended the government measures, saying, It's clear a country cannot accept such pressure from migration and not react"
          href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              Thanos Plevris defended the government measures, saying, It's
              clear a country cannot accept such pressure from migration and not
              react. Credits: La Derecha Diario</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Greece reported that over 7,000 migrants
            reached Crete between January and late June, with most coming from
            Libya, Egypt, Yemen, and Sudan. The migration minister called this
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-influx-an-invasion?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >influx an ‚Äúinvasion‚Äù</a
            >
            and urged Europe to enact strict measures. Migrants arriving from
            war-torn places were intercepted at sea and sent back, even after
            providing evidence.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The cause:</strong> Recently, Greece suspended processing
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-asylum-applications-from-north-africa?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >asylum applications from North Africa</a
            >
            for the next three months despite
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-criticism-from-the-un?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >criticism from the UN</a
            >
            and the EU humanitarian groups. The country wants to
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-tackle-trafficking?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >tackle trafficking</a
            >
            by warlord Gen. Khalifa Haftar from Libya, and it wants to balance
            international law and national interests. There is also fear among
            locals over security and that the migrant presence can hamper their
            tourism appeal.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>On the ground:</strong> The migrants are held in former
            exhibition centers in Crete, which have poor sanitation and are
            increasingly becoming overcrowded. The
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h1-5-heatwave-in-greece?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >heatwave in Greece</a
            >
            is affecting the detainees, and aid boxes have remained closed as
            officials fear provoking a fight. Officials arrest the asylum
            seekers from Sudan and other African countries, not giving them time
            to explain their story.
          </p>
